726296f-a.text:
Calamus Ave., south side, east from Elk Road to Grand Ave., showing at the left, Nos. 7481 and 7442 Calamus Ave. In the background on the east side of Grand Ave., are seen some two family frame structures. The peaked roof structure (clothing hanging on lines in back thereof) was the original Rapelje homestead and was in the hands of the Gray family from 1873 to 1909; being demolished early in 1932. This is a set of four views. In No. 4 may also be seen the steeple of St. Alberts Church and the Brooklyn Union Gas Company's tanks.
May 1923.
View 2: March 1923.
View 3: January 1923.
View 4: May 1925.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

726295f-b.text:
Calamus Avenue, east from Elks Road to Grand Avenue, showing in three views on the south side of the Avenue, partially submerged, the Rapelye farmhouse. This house was renovated in 1923 and razed in early 1932. J. Gray was the owner from 1873 to 1891. In 1923 Fred Bushing was an occupant. Views one and two show also a branch of the Long Island Railroad and buildings on Grand Avenue which are seen at the right background.
June 1924
Views 1,2 and 3
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
